quest_title: For the reactions \(PCl_5 \leftrightarrow PCl_3+Cl_2\), forward reaction at constant temperature is favoured by ;
ans1_txt: Introducing an inert gas at constant  vol
ans2_txt: Introducing chlorine gas at constant volume
ans3_txt: Introducing an inert gas at constant pressure
ans4_txt: Decreasing the volume of the container
explanation_txt:
Introducing an inert gas at constant pressure makes the reaction to proceed towards side of higher moles.*

(Introducing inert gas at constant volume has no effect)

So, forward reaction is favoured. [Since no. of moles of products (2) is greater than reactants (1)]

*Introducing inert gas at constant pressure increases the overall volume. So, concentration of both reagents and products decreases. To increase the concentration [and restore the equilibrium], higher no. of moles is favored.

quest_title: Melting point of ice
explanation_txt:
Melting point of ice decreases with increase in pressure (as ice expands on solidification).

This can be explained using LeChatelier's principle. The principle states that when a system is in equilibrium, any external changes that try to take it out of equilibrium (like applying pressure to ice) will cause the system to adjust in a way to counteract that change. In this case, if you increase the pressure on the ice the ice-water system wants to try to lower it again. It can do that by making itself fit into a smaller volume. But since water fills a smaller volume when it's liquid, rather than solid, it will go to a lower melting point -- allowing more solid to become liquid.

-Brent Nelson, Ph.D. Student, UC Berkeley
